<paragraph blockId="35.[167,780,422,1407]" pageId="35" pageNumber="966">
<emphasis box="[168,779,636,660]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="966" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,330,636,660]" pageId="35" pageNumber="966">Identification.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scherberich &amp; P. C. Boyce (Scherberich and Boyce" authorityYear="2013" box="[337,635,636,660]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Schismatoglottis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="35" pageNumber="966" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="scintillans">
<emphasis box="[337,635,636,660]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="966">Schismatoglottis scintillans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
most closely
</emphasis>
approaches 
<taxonomicName box="[297,428,669,693]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Schismatoglottis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="35" pageNumber="966" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="decipiens">
<emphasis box="[297,428,669,693]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="966">S. decipiens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
A.Hay and 
<taxonomicName box="[564,745,669,693]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Schismatoglottis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="35" pageNumber="966" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="trusmadiensis">
<emphasis box="[564,745,669,693]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="966">S. trusmadiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the pistillate flower zone extensively (≥ ½) adnate to the spathe, but it is readily distinguished from both species by the combination of a much longer proportion of this adnation (5/6 of the entire pistillate zone vs. ½), and by scintillating leaf blades. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scherberich &amp; P. C. Boyce (Scherberich and Boyce" authorityYear="2013" box="[448,747,838,862]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Schismatoglottis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="35" pageNumber="966" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="scintillans">
<emphasis box="[448,747,838,862]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="966">Schismatoglottis scintillans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is specifically distinguished from 
<taxonomicName box="[504,632,872,896]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Schismatoglottis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="35" pageNumber="966" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="decipiens">
<emphasis box="[504,632,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="966">S. decipiens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the staminate flower zone half enclosed (not fully exerted) from the lower spathe, and by lacking a naked interstice between the staminate and pistillate zones. From 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="966">
<taxonomicName box="[594,773,973,997]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Schismatoglottis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="35" pageNumber="966" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="trusmadiensis">S. trusmadiensis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scherberich &amp; P. C. Boyce (Scherberich and Boyce" authorityYear="2013" box="[167,306,1007,1031]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Schismatoglottis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="35" pageNumber="966" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="scintillans">S. scintillans</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is further distinguished by a bullet-shaped appendix being much wider than the top of the staminate flower zone (vs. appendix bluntly conoid, and indistinctly wider than the top of the staminate zone) and by the overall much more compact stature, and ovate-sagittate, variegated, velvety leaf blades (vs. hastate-sagittate, plain glossy green) (
<bibRefCitation author="Scherberich D &amp; Boyce PC" box="[324,631,1209,1234]" pageId="35" pageNumber="966" pagination="87 - 90" refId="ref51662" refString="Scherberich D, Boyce PC (2013) Studies on Schismatoglottideae (Araceae) of Borneo XXVI - Schismatoglottis scintillans, a new species with horticultural potential from Sabah, Malaysian Borneo. Willdenowia 43: 87 - 90." type="journal article" year="2013">Scherberich and Boyce 2013</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="966" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="35.[167,780,422,1407]" pageId="35" pageNumber="966">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,466,1248,1272]" pageId="35" pageNumber="966">Distribution and ecology.</emphasis>
Endemic to 
<collectingRegion box="[614,683,1248,1272]" country="Malaysia" name="Sabah" pageId="35" pageNumber="966">Sabah</collectingRegion>
. Known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[321,369,1283,1307]" pageId="35" pageNumber="966">type</typeStatus>
locality in Keningau, Apin Apin, elevation ca. 
<quantity box="[280,346,1316,1340]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.1" pageId="35" pageNumber="966" unit="m" value="610.0">610 m</quantity>
(“ 
<quantity box="[370,456,1316,1340]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.096" pageId="35" pageNumber="966" unit="ft" value="2000.0">2000 ft</quantity>
”). Grows terrestrially in very shaded riverine forests on wet alluvial soils, at ca. 
<quantity metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="35" pageNumber="966" unit="m" value="600.0">600 m</quantity>
elev.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
